{{Infobox Website |name = Asteroid Zoo |logo =Avatar asteroids.jpg |logo_size =200px |url = [http://www.asteroidzoo.org/ asteroidzoo.org] |commercial = no |type = [[Citizen science]] project |language = English, Polish |registration = Yes, but not mandatory |author = [[Planetary Resources]]; [[Chris Lewicki|C. Lewicki]], [[Matthew Beasley|M. Beasley]], et al.<ref name=founders>{{cite web|title=Asteroid Zoo: About|url=http://www.asteroidzoo.org/#/about|website=Asteroid Zoo|accessdate=6 February 2015}}</ref> |launch_date = 24 June 2014<ref name=startdate>{{cite web|title=Welcome to Asteroid Zoo!|url=http://blog.asteroidzoo.org/2014/06/24/welcome-to-asteroid-zoo/|website=blog.asteroidzoo.org|publisher=asteroid zoo|accessdate=6 February 2015}}</ref> |current_status = paused }}
'''Asteroid Zoo''' is a citizen science project run by the [[Zooniverse (citizen science project)|Zooniverse]] and [[Planetary Resources]], to use volunteer classifications to find unknown asteroids using old [[Catalina Sky Survey]] data.<ref name=space.com>{{cite web|last1=Wall|first1=Mike|title=Asteroid Zoo Asks Public to Find Dangerous Space Rocks|url=http://www.space.com/26349-asteroid-zoo-zooniverse-planetary-resources.html|website=Space.com|publisher=[[Purch]]|accessdate=6 February 2015}}</ref> The main goals of the project are to search for undiscovered asteroids in order to protect the planet by locating potentially harmful near-Earth Asteroids, locate targets for future [[asteroid mining]], study the solar system, and study the potential uses and advantages of people looking through the images over computers.<ref>{{cite web|title=item from NASA NEWS|url=http://talk.asteroidzoo.org/#/boards/BAZ0000001/discussions/DAZ00007td|website=talk.asteroidzoo.org|accessdate=6 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.asteroidzoo.org/#/about|title = Asteroid Zoo: About|date = |accessdate = |website = |publisher = |last = |first = }}</ref> It was created along with the ARKYD project through [[Kickstarter]], funded with just over 1.5 million dollars.<ref name=kickstarter>{{cite web|title=ARKYD: A space telescope for everyone|url=https://www.kickstarter.com/projects/arkydforeveryone/arkyd-a-space-telescope-for-everyone-0/description|website=kickstarter|accessdate=6 February 2015}}</ref>
The AsteroidZoo community has exhausted the data that were available. With all the data examined they paused the experiment.<ref>[https://www.asteroidzoo.org/ Archived Zooniverse Project: Asteroid Zoo]</ref> Asteroid Zoo produced several scientific publications.<ref>[https://www.zooniverse.org/about/publications All publications] (2017)</ref>
